00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:57.430
goes wrong in everything
from finance, engineering,

00:02:57.430 --> 00:03:00.010
statistics, medicine,
you name it,

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:03.430
I can show-- it's an excuse
to talk about the maths that's

00:03:03.430 --> 00:03:06.970
required for these areas
of our modern society.

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:09.310
And so obviously, maths
works pretty flawlessly

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:11.530
most of the time, so
much so that most people

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:14.050
have no idea how dependent
we are on mathematics.

00:03:14.050 --> 00:03:16.300
And people often don't
value maths for that reason.

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:18.190
So I thought, this
is a great excuse

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:20.230
to just talk about
all the places maths

00:03:20.230 --> 00:03:24.820
is used, but by using things
going wrong as my way in.

00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:29.367
And actually, because I
used to be a maths teacher--

00:03:29.367 --> 00:03:30.450
actually, give me a cheer.

00:03:30.450 --> 00:03:31.857
Any maths teachers in?

00:03:31.857 --> 00:03:34.990
[WEAK CHEER]

00:03:34.990 --> 00:03:38.020
Hiding at the top,
not sounding exciting.

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:39.520
It's the end of
half term, isn't it?

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:40.840
Right, OK, there you are.

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:42.910
So I used to be a
maths teacher, just

00:03:42.910 --> 00:03:45.310
like the fine people cowering
at the top of the room.

00:03:45.310 --> 00:03:49.210
And then I left teaching.

00:03:49.210 --> 00:03:51.938
But I still remembered how a lot
of young people-- because when

00:03:51.938 --> 00:03:54.230
you were at school, you were
forced to do maths, right?

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:56.060
When you're forced to
do it, a other people

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:57.520
perceive mathematics
as the subject

00:03:57.520 --> 00:03:59.020
where you have to get it right.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:01.150
Getting the right
answer is everything.

00:04:01.150 --> 00:04:03.430
It's the be all, end
all of mathematics.

00:04:03.430 --> 00:04:05.560
And as a teacher, you
know that that's not

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:07.640
always strictly true, right?

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:09.947
Maths is about trying
something and getting it wrong,

00:04:09.947 --> 00:04:11.530
and then trying it
again and hopefully

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:14.190
getting it less wrong,
and then more wrong.

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:17.500
And hopefully it converges
in on the minimal amount

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:18.510
of wrong possible.

00:04:18.510 --> 00:04:22.540
But it's a long, slow process
of not understanding it and not

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:23.350
doing it well.

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:25.150
And it's always
very disappointing

00:04:25.150 --> 00:04:28.230
when students, or
even people in--

00:04:28.230 --> 00:04:33.010
standard-issue humans are afraid
to try some maths because they

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:34.810
think if they don't
get the right answer,

00:04:34.810 --> 00:04:36.287
they haven't done it correctly.

00:04:36.287 --> 00:04:37.120
And that's not true.

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:38.870
If you get the wrong
answer, you may still

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:41.632
be correct in your
trying it, right?

00:04:41.632 --> 00:04:43.840
Mathematics is about learning
and teaching your brain

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:44.382
how to think.

00:04:44.382 --> 00:04:47.560
And so I thought, how can I
bring that approach to what

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:51.243
will otherwise just be a random
collection of maths mistakes

00:04:51.243 --> 00:04:52.660
that haven't got
any real meaning?

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:56.380
And I started with an
inspirational poster

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:59.290
that I had when I was a teacher.

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:02.530
And inspirational
posters are the staple

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:03.447
of the teaching world.

00:05:03.447 --> 00:05:05.238
It's what you decorate
your classroom with.

00:05:05.238 --> 00:05:07.110
And this was one of my
absolute favourites.

00:05:07.110 --> 00:05:09.070
They you are--
education works best

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:11.620
when all the parts are working.

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:14.350
Now, let me just break
this down for you.

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:17.900
So you've got cogs representing
students, teachers,

00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:18.432
and parents.

00:05:18.432 --> 00:05:20.390
The trouble is, when that
big cog on the right,

00:05:20.390 --> 00:05:22.540
which represents
students-- if that rotates,

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:26.020
let's say, clockwise, because
it meshes with teachers,

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:28.480
teachers have to
rotate anti-clockwise.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:29.560
That's all very nice.

00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:31.185
But neither of them
are going anywhere,

00:05:31.185 --> 00:05:33.250
because parents are jamming
up the whole system.

00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:35.880
[LAUGHS]

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:43.460
Surprisingly more applause from
the teachers than the parents.

00:05:43.460 --> 00:05:47.310
Surprisingly accurate poster,
in my humble experience.

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:48.990
And then obviously,
people just haven't

00:05:48.990 --> 00:05:51.510
thought through the geometry
of this situation, right?

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:52.950
If you have cogs,
they have to go

00:05:52.950 --> 00:05:55.680
clockwise, anti-clockwise,
clockwise, anti-clockwise.

00:05:55.680 --> 00:05:59.310
So when Manchester were
unveiling their new approach

00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:03.330
to public transport, they went
with the classic three-cog

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:06.540
making the city work together,
although people did point

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:10.800
out and proceed to render
in 3D that that's just

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:11.820
this one point of view.

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:15.285
Possibly, from the
side, it's fine.

00:06:15.285 --> 00:06:16.620
It's like, well played.

00:06:16.620 --> 00:06:17.130
Well played.

00:06:17.130 --> 00:06:20.910
If all you see is this, you
don't-- look, that's deep.

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:24.750
They were thinking-- they
were several steps ahead,

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:28.920
until I saw an article where
President Trump in the United

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:31.710
States was negotiating the North
American Free Trade Agreement.

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:34.020
And when that was
put in the newspapers

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:37.200
to show how all the working
parts of North America

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:39.060
should be moving
in unison, papers

00:06:39.060 --> 00:06:42.390
used this illustration,
where you've already used

00:06:42.390 --> 00:06:43.582
your third dimension, right?

00:06:43.582 --> 00:06:44.790
You're not getting that back.

00:06:44.790 --> 00:06:50.730
So I paid money, I paid good
money to licence that image

00:06:50.730 --> 00:06:53.730
to put it in my book just
so I could use the caption,

00:06:53.730 --> 00:06:58.253
"Making Cogs Great Again,"
so totally worth it.

00:06:58.253 --> 00:07:01.880
[APPLAUSE]

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:04.830
And finally, two-pound coins--

00:07:04.830 --> 00:07:08.538
when the two-pound coin came
out to celebrate the millennium,

00:07:08.538 --> 00:07:10.080
there was a competition
to design it.

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:11.610
This was the winning entry.

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:13.650
And it's got different
concentric, I guess,

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:18.360
circles, bits, where it shows
different stages of UK history.

00:07:18.360 --> 00:07:21.870
And the middle one, your
kind of mechanical age here,

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:23.570
is a series of cogs.

00:07:23.570 --> 00:07:26.697
And because if a cog goes
clockwise, the one next to it

00:07:26.697 --> 00:07:29.280
has to go anti-clockwise, then
clockwise, then anti-clockwise,

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:32.100
you have to have an even number
of cogs as you go around.

00:07:32.100 --> 00:07:35.280
The two-pound coin has
an odd number of cogs.

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:36.660
It would not work.

00:07:36.660 --> 00:07:41.490
People on the internet
were unimpressed and smug

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:42.570
in equal measure.

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:45.450
And the Royal Mint put
out a statement saying

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:47.020
that it doesn't matter, right?

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:49.080
It's just, what are
you going on about?

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:51.178
It's just meant to
represent that age.

00:07:51.178 --> 00:07:52.470
And I was like, that's curious.

00:07:52.470 --> 00:07:56.210
But I wonder, because
there's a 50-50--

00:07:56.210 --> 00:07:57.960
I don't know what would
be a great example

00:07:57.960 --> 00:07:59.910
to simulate a 50-50 chance.

00:07:59.910 --> 00:08:02.940
Imagine flipping
something, right?

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:05.370
It could go either way.

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:07.005
If you do it at
random, you get an odd

00:08:07.005 --> 00:08:08.370
or an even number of cogs.

00:08:08.370 --> 00:08:11.730
And so I looked up the person
who designed this coin,

00:08:11.730 --> 00:08:13.350
a guy called Bruce Russian.

00:08:13.350 --> 00:08:15.450
He's an art teacher in Norfolk.

00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:18.270
And on his website, he's
got his original design,

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:20.520
which would have worked.

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:23.190
It's an even number of cogs.

00:08:23.190 --> 00:08:26.520
The actual coin that was
made, these three cogs

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:29.190
were removed, which meant
that it wouldn't work.

00:08:29.190 --> 00:08:30.330
I was like, wow.

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:32.789
He had it right, and
the Royal Mint broke it.

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:34.289
But was that deliberate?

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:35.490
So I sent him an email.

00:08:35.490 --> 00:08:36.929
I said, hey, I'm really sorry.

00:08:36.929 --> 00:08:38.700
I'm sure people have
pointed this out

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:42.000
I'm just curious, because
I noticed you got it right.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:43.169
Was that deliberate?

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:44.159
Did you think about it?

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:45.160
Was it a concern?

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:45.743
What happened?

00:08:45.743 --> 00:08:47.410
I'm writing a book
about maths mistakes.

00:08:47.410 --> 00:08:49.620
I'm curious to know, what
was your thought process?

00:08:49.620 --> 00:08:53.220
And he replied to say that he
didn't think, as an artist,

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:55.080
it should have to be correct.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:56.640
He thought it was
representative,

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:57.600
a bunch of cogs.

00:08:57.600 --> 00:09:00.510
It doesn't make a difference
to the artistic worth

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:01.380
of the design.

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:03.790
And to be honest, I
kind of agree with him.

00:09:03.790 --> 00:09:08.100
He then said that he decided
to make it work anyway,

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:11.700
because otherwise, he would
get loads of annoying emails

00:09:11.700 --> 00:09:12.330
from pedants.

00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:14.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:18.370
I don't know why that was
in bold, but there you go.

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:19.870
And so yeah, so he
just thought, ah,

00:09:19.870 --> 00:09:20.770
people are going to complain.

00:09:20.770 --> 00:09:22.395
They're going to go
on and on about it.

00:09:22.395 --> 00:09:24.108
And now, this is the
unfortunate edge,

00:09:24.108 --> 00:09:26.400
because when I was writing
a book about maths mistakes,

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:28.068
I didn't want it to
be all about niche,

00:09:28.068 --> 00:09:30.360
theoretical maths problems,
of which there are things--

00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:32.100
people thought they had proved
something, and they hadn't.

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:34.470
And that's interesting
to a small demographic

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:35.970
that includes this guy.

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:39.220
But then there's also the kind
of pedantic, ah, you're wrong,

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:41.190
I'm right, which
is the opposite of,

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:42.960
it's fine to make
mistakes, which

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:45.780
is one of the things
I want to get across.

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:47.910
And a lot of mistakes
don't really matter.

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:50.250
So I hunted down a
copy of this book.

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:53.650
I remembered this from years
and years and years ago.

00:09:53.650 --> 00:09:54.780
I didn't have as a child.

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:56.140
I must've seen some--

00:09:56.140 --> 00:09:57.990
I mean, a lot of my
friends procreate.

00:09:57.990 --> 00:09:59.920
And I saw somewhere this book.

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:01.470
This is a Sesame Street book.

00:10:01.470 --> 00:10:06.450
This is Ernie expressing his
dislike of the possibility

00:10:06.450 --> 00:10:09.060
of being forced to live on the
moon, which feels like a niche

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:10.350
concern, but there you go.

00:10:10.350 --> 00:10:12.945
And I hunted down a
copy of this book.

00:10:12.945 --> 00:10:14.070
I found it on the internet.

00:10:14.070 --> 00:10:16.470
And there's one thing about
this which really bothers me.

00:10:16.470 --> 00:10:17.370
It's not important.

00:10:17.370 --> 00:10:19.530
It's not a major issue.

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:21.330
Does anyone, apart
from the child

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:23.400
who had a very loud
epiphany over there,

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:25.140
like to tell me
what's wrong with it?

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:26.850
There's stars where
the moon should be.

00:10:26.850 --> 00:10:28.920
There's stars where
the moon should be.

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:30.660
You are 100% correct.

00:10:30.660 --> 00:10:33.270
What are these?

00:10:33.270 --> 00:10:36.690
There's not a hole in the moon.

00:10:36.690 --> 00:10:39.390
As far as I'm aware, in
the extended Sesame Street

00:10:39.390 --> 00:10:42.360
universe, there are
not Muppet bases

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:44.520
that we can see twinkling
on the moon, right?

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:46.710
And so you often
see a crescent moon.

00:10:46.710 --> 00:10:48.900
And then you see stars
shining through it.

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:51.630
And no, the moon is, well,
from our point of view, a disc,

00:10:51.630 --> 00:10:52.170
right?

00:10:52.170 --> 00:10:53.250
And it's always there.

00:10:53.250 --> 00:10:54.270
It blocks out the stars.

00:10:54.270 --> 00:10:56.550
We do see different bits,
depending on how it's lit.

00:10:56.550 --> 00:10:58.740
And that's an artistic
version of that.

00:10:58.740 --> 00:11:00.870
Bizarrely, I'm fine
with that, right?

00:11:00.870 --> 00:11:04.380
But I'm like, ugh, they
shouldn't show stars

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:05.760
through the crescent
moon, right?

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:08.518
Come on, bit of
astronomy, everybody.

00:11:08.518 --> 00:11:10.560
And then I was looking
around for other examples.

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:12.990
And actually, Sesame Street
have done this more than once.

00:11:12.990 --> 00:11:18.300
And I was looking at,
separately, the licence plates

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:20.860
from the state of Texas.

00:11:20.860 --> 00:11:22.980
So this is a plate from Texas.

00:11:22.980 --> 00:11:25.295
And as you can see, it's
celebrating the fact

00:11:25.295 --> 00:11:26.920
that the shuttle was
involved in Texas.

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:27.920
And there's the shuttle.

00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:29.595
That's not a bad
angle, actually,

00:11:29.595 --> 00:11:30.720
for the shuttle taking off.

00:11:30.720 --> 00:11:32.940
That's surprisingly--
it hasn't got any

00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:34.830
of its boosters or anything.

00:11:34.830 --> 00:11:35.850
Maybe that's it landing.

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:36.392
I don't know.

00:11:36.392 --> 00:11:40.170
I was distracted by
over here, that star.

00:11:40.170 --> 00:11:44.040
That star is dangerously
close to that--

00:11:44.040 --> 00:11:45.870
but the only way I
could know for sure

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:51.400
would be to somehow buy some
licence plates from Texas.

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:52.090
So I did that.

00:11:52.090 --> 00:11:53.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:56.260
And they arrived in the post.

00:11:56.260 --> 00:11:58.420
There we are.

00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:00.340
This is actually genuinely--

00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:03.280
I scanned it so I could get
a high-resolution version,

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:05.620
because all the ones
online were too low-res.

00:12:05.620 --> 00:12:08.230
And if you zoom
right in, and you

00:12:08.230 --> 00:12:10.270
fill in the rest of the moon--

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:12.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:12.250 --> 00:12:17.350
Texas, undone by a lone star.

00:12:17.350 --> 00:12:19.180
Oh, people have
since pointed out

00:12:19.180 --> 00:12:22.360
that maybe it's marking where
the first Apollo landing

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:23.390
site was.

00:12:23.390 --> 00:12:26.140
And it's very close.

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:28.420
I might give them that,
to be entirely honest.

00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:31.360
But these problems--
they're not--

00:12:31.360 --> 00:12:33.730
OK, if we're just
talking about, are there

00:12:33.730 --> 00:12:35.710
practical implications
for the problems?

00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:37.418
In this case, I mean,
don't get me wrong.

00:12:37.418 --> 00:12:39.100
I'm a big fan of
getting maths correct,

00:12:39.100 --> 00:12:42.460
and good maths PR, and
mass being important.

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:45.160
But just practically,
are they important?

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:49.180
And sadly, in those cases, not
really, not really important.

00:12:49.180 --> 00:12:51.060
But sometimes, the
maths can be important.

00:12:51.060 --> 00:12:53.770
So you may have noticed,
I am dancing around

00:12:53.770 --> 00:12:57.100
a very large Jenga tower.

00:12:57.100 --> 00:13:00.370
And I thought I would have
this set up during my show

00:13:00.370 --> 00:13:03.940
to artificially increase
the amount of suspense

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:05.670
for narrative purposes.

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:06.790
No.

00:13:06.790 --> 00:13:12.320
So this is to show a fantastic
effect about resonance.

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:15.065
So this is a building.

00:13:15.065 --> 00:13:16.690
And we're going to
show you in a second

00:13:16.690 --> 00:13:20.530
how a building resonates,
hopefully, to destruction.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:22.450
We will see how lucky we get--

00:13:22.450 --> 00:13:26.110
or unlucky, depending on what
I'm trying to do at the time.

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:28.090
Normally, you will hear
resonance discussed

00:13:28.090 --> 00:13:29.500
when it comes to bridges.

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:30.875
And so there are
a lot of bridges

00:13:30.875 --> 00:13:33.100
which have had resonance
problems, dating back into--

00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:35.830
I think the earliest one I've
come across was in the 1800s,

00:13:35.830 --> 00:13:39.838
up near Manchester,
where Salford is now.

00:13:39.838 --> 00:13:40.630
There was a bridge.

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:42.797
And there were some troops
marching over the bridge.

00:13:42.797 --> 00:13:44.350
Because they were
all in step, they

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:48.190
hit a resonance
frequency of the bridge.

00:13:48.190 --> 00:13:50.380
And the bridge start to
move, which, apparently,

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:51.860
they thought was kind of fun.

00:13:51.860 --> 00:13:53.890
So they started
singing a tune to match

00:13:53.890 --> 00:13:57.100
the bouncing bridge, really
got involved, and it collapsed.

00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:59.470
And no one died.

00:13:59.470 --> 00:14:00.610
No one died.

00:14:00.610 --> 00:14:02.230
It's OK.

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:03.730
It's difficult
writing-- because you

00:14:03.730 --> 00:14:05.980
know when you cover engineering
and medical mistakes,

00:14:05.980 --> 00:14:07.522
when I was putting
the book together,

00:14:07.522 --> 00:14:11.110
I'm like, every second
story, everybody dies.

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:14.200
I can't have a comedy book
about maths, and every second--

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:17.200
every couple pages, and
then everybody died.

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:19.720
So I think, in all the
engineering examples

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:21.670
I'm going to give you,
nobody died, I think.

00:14:21.670 --> 00:14:24.060
And all the aviation stories
in the book, nobody died.

00:14:24.060 --> 00:14:26.560
Don't get me wrong, people do
die in aviation problems, just

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:28.060
not the ones I put in the book.

00:14:28.060 --> 00:14:30.900
So that was the problem with
the bridge up near Manchester.

00:14:30.900 --> 00:14:32.650
In London, you've still
got this one here.

00:14:32.650 --> 00:14:33.970
This is the Albert Bridge.

00:14:33.970 --> 00:14:36.970
All troops must break step
when marching over this bridge.

00:14:36.970 --> 00:14:38.920
That sign is still there.

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:40.930
They must break step.

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:43.427
Interestingly, though,
they must not break dance--

00:14:43.427 --> 00:14:44.260
very different rule.

00:14:44.260 --> 00:14:45.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:45.610 --> 00:14:47.350
And when I mention
this, a lot of

00:14:47.350 --> 00:14:50.350
you are now thinking of
one of two famous bridges--

00:14:50.350 --> 00:14:53.230
Tacoma Narrows Bridge--
this was a bridge

00:14:53.230 --> 00:14:55.990
in the US, art deco bridge,
absolutely phenomenal,

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:58.150
incredible amount of twist.

00:14:58.150 --> 00:15:00.850
Now, that's not your
standard resonance

00:15:00.850 --> 00:15:04.180
from just people marching on
it, or even bursts of wind,

00:15:04.180 --> 00:15:06.310
as you will occasionally
read online.

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:07.540
This is resonating.

00:15:07.540 --> 00:15:08.620
But this is flutter.

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:11.710
This is aerodynamic flutter
from the wind coming up

00:15:11.710 --> 00:15:12.970
the valley where it was.

00:15:12.970 --> 00:15:16.830
And the flutter basically caused
this runaway feedback loop

00:15:16.830 --> 00:15:20.260
where, as bridge came up,
more wind pushed it higher up.

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:22.960
When it finally bounced back and
down, more wind pushed it down.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:28.060
And you got this feedback, which
led it to go more and more.

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:31.390
Someone finally decided maybe
they should leave their car.

00:15:31.390 --> 00:15:34.690
Also, you've got the
Millennium Bridge in London.

00:15:34.690 --> 00:15:37.420
This was opened
in the year 2000.

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:39.283
And it was only open
for a couple of days

00:15:39.283 --> 00:15:40.450
before they had to close it.

00:15:40.450 --> 00:15:42.370
They looked at the footage.

00:15:42.370 --> 00:15:44.770
Now, if everyone's
walking randomly,

00:15:44.770 --> 00:15:47.020
it should be fine,
because they're not all

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:48.910
going to match one
particular frequency.

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:50.202
But they looked at the footage.

00:15:50.202 --> 00:15:52.810
About 20% of the pedestrians--
admittedly, it's quite crowded.

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:55.810
But 20% of them were
all marching in sync.

00:15:55.810 --> 00:15:59.830
The bridge is moving about 7
and 1/2 centimetres either way,

00:15:59.830 --> 00:16:01.960
which is about 7
and 1/2 too many.

00:16:01.960 --> 00:16:05.140
And so they had to close it and
do all sorts of crazy things

00:16:05.140 --> 00:16:06.970
to damp it, because
what was happening was,

00:16:06.970 --> 00:16:08.410
the bridge was moving a bit.

00:16:08.410 --> 00:16:09.748
And people were moving with it.

00:16:09.748 --> 00:16:12.040
And so they were then stepping
in time with the bridge.

00:16:12.040 --> 00:16:15.225
So the bridge moving was causing
the pedestrians to synchronise.

00:16:15.225 --> 00:16:16.600
And the pedestrians
synchronising

00:16:16.600 --> 00:16:17.892
was causing the bridge to move.

00:16:17.892 --> 00:16:19.340
And you get this feedback loop.

00:16:19.340 --> 00:16:25.170
The official wording was, it was
synchronous lateral excitation.

00:16:25.170 --> 00:16:26.140
It was a feedback.

00:16:26.140 --> 00:16:27.970
Energy was going in,
and it was matching

00:16:27.970 --> 00:16:29.650
the resonant
frequency, which is,

00:16:29.650 --> 00:16:32.062
of course, totally terrifying.

00:16:32.062 --> 00:16:33.270
I'm more interested, though--

00:16:33.270 --> 00:16:35.440
I've become obsessed with--
the bridges are one thing.

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:36.315
They're easy to move.

00:16:36.315 --> 00:16:37.960
And we kind of-- for
the most part now,

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:39.460
we get-- which is
why the Millennium

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:40.420
Bridge was so amazing.

00:16:40.420 --> 00:16:43.150
For the most part now
bridges, work fine.

00:16:43.150 --> 00:16:44.590
Buildings, less so.

00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:48.760
So there was a building
in South Korea in 2011,

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:50.250
which is disturbingly recently.

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:52.540
Anything within a decade,
I find terrifying.

00:16:52.540 --> 00:16:54.370
It was a 39-story building.

00:16:54.370 --> 00:16:57.790
And one day, in 2011, the
people on the 38th floor

00:16:57.790 --> 00:16:59.290
evacuated because
they thought there

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:00.400
was an earthquake or something.

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:01.483
It was shaking like crazy.

00:17:01.483 --> 00:17:02.552
They left the building.

00:17:02.552 --> 00:17:04.510
No one else knew what
they were going on about.

00:17:04.510 --> 00:17:05.979
The building was fine.

00:17:05.979 --> 00:17:07.069
They were like, what?

00:17:07.069 --> 00:17:08.500
They did an investigation.

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:12.069
And they recreated this,
so this is genuinely true.

00:17:12.069 --> 00:17:17.079
It turns out, on the 12th
floor was an exercise class.

00:17:17.079 --> 00:17:19.810
And about 20 people
decided to exercise

00:17:19.810 --> 00:17:22.119
to a different song that day.

00:17:22.119 --> 00:17:27.790
They exercised to Snap's
"I've Got the Power."

00:17:27.790 --> 00:17:30.745
If you're unfamiliar with
Snap's "I've Got the Power"--

00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:36.040
That would be better if
it was a dramatic, uh--

00:17:36.040 --> 00:17:39.000
if you're unfamiliar with
Snap's "I've Got the Power"--

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:39.940
[MUSIC PLAYS BRIEFLY]

00:17:39.940 --> 00:17:43.000
And that's as much as I can play
without the Royal Institution

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.260
getting a copyright
strike on their channel.

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:47.372
So they danced to that song.

00:17:47.372 --> 00:17:49.330
The song happened to
match a resonant frequency

00:17:49.330 --> 00:17:49.997
of the building.

00:17:49.997 --> 00:17:53.200
And the 38th floor moved
10 times more than normal--

00:17:53.200 --> 00:17:54.220
absolutely incredible.

00:17:54.220 --> 00:17:55.990
So when people design
buildings, they

00:17:55.990 --> 00:17:57.400
have to try and factor this in.

00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:00.010
And it is a big problem, which
is what-- this is actually

00:18:00.010 --> 00:18:03.283
kind of a teaching
aid for learning

00:18:03.283 --> 00:18:04.450
about resonance in building.

00:18:04.450 --> 00:18:06.310
And I've borrowed this
off a friend of mine

00:18:06.310 --> 00:18:08.040
who is an engineer.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:09.790
And they've actually
come along to give me

00:18:09.790 --> 00:18:13.270
a hand, because I am not
qualified to run this,

00:18:13.270 --> 00:18:15.440
and see what it can
show us about resonance.

00:18:15.440 --> 00:18:17.440
So can you please
welcome to the stage,

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:19.697
from the University of
Bath, Paul Shepherd.

00:18:19.697 --> 00:18:20.551
[APPLAUSE]

00:18:20.551 --> 00:18:23.620
There he is.

00:18:23.620 --> 00:18:24.680
Welcome, welcome.

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:26.850
Thank you.

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:29.730
I haven't seen you since
we put this back together.

00:18:29.730 --> 00:18:32.640
OK, it's been minutes.

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:33.907
So don't pick that up.

00:18:33.907 --> 00:18:34.740
Yeah, I get nervous.

00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:38.550
OK, so first of all, what do you
do at the University of Bath?

00:18:38.550 --> 00:18:42.540
I teach mathematics
to civil engineers.

00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:45.060
I research how we
can use computers

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:47.200
to design better buildings.

00:18:47.200 --> 00:18:51.510
And I've also got a role in
our Institute of Mathematical

00:18:51.510 --> 00:18:54.540
Innovation, helping companies
with their maths problems.

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:55.210
Fantastic.

00:18:55.210 --> 00:18:58.080
Notice how he started and ended
with maths to keep me happy.

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:01.560
So you use this in your
lectures, I believe.

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:02.400
Yes.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:06.750
And just talk us through,
what is this bit of kit?

00:19:06.750 --> 00:19:09.390
Literally, it's a
washing machine motor.

00:19:09.390 --> 00:19:10.680
But let's not go there, right?

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:11.290
It really is.

00:19:11.290 --> 00:19:13.470
This is a washing
machine motor in a box.

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:15.150
There's some magic in the box.

00:19:15.150 --> 00:19:19.470
It causes the base to move
back and forth, vibrate.

00:19:19.470 --> 00:19:22.020
And I have here a button that
you're not qualified to press--

00:19:22.020 --> 00:19:22.645
That's the one.

00:19:22.645 --> 00:19:26.910
--and a dial to make
it go faster or slower.

00:19:26.910 --> 00:19:28.320
Is there like a safe slow?

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:29.055
Can we--

00:19:29.055 --> 00:19:30.010
We can do it really--

00:19:30.010 --> 00:19:30.770
Or do you want to leave it?

00:19:30.770 --> 00:19:31.560
What do you want to do?

00:19:31.560 --> 00:19:31.860
No, no, no, it's fine.

00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:32.550
OK, here we go.

00:19:32.550 --> 00:19:32.850
OK, so--

00:19:32.850 --> 00:19:33.490
I can do it slow.

00:19:33.490 --> 00:19:34.510
--we'll show it in action.

00:19:34.510 --> 00:19:35.160
See if it still works.

00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:36.535
I'll catch it if
it goes to fall.

00:19:36.535 --> 00:19:37.470
Really slow, yeah?

00:19:37.470 --> 00:19:38.340
Like, you know--

00:19:38.340 --> 00:19:42.330
Oh, that is fantastically slow.

00:19:42.330 --> 00:19:44.830
If anyone starts watching the
video right now, they're like,

00:19:44.830 --> 00:19:46.205
it is playing at
the wrong speed.

00:19:46.205 --> 00:19:47.387
Anyone still awake?

00:19:47.387 --> 00:19:48.220
So that's it, right?

00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:50.210
And on top of this, we've
built a Jenga tower.

00:19:50.210 --> 00:19:50.560
Yeah.

00:19:50.560 --> 00:19:51.935
And what we wanted
to demonstrate

00:19:51.935 --> 00:19:54.640
with this is that if you hit the
resonant frequency of the Jenga

00:19:54.640 --> 00:19:57.110
tower, it will fall over.

00:19:57.110 --> 00:19:59.350
But to make it a
challenge, first we're

00:19:59.350 --> 00:20:02.500
going to start with a frequency
where it won't fall over.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:04.610
So we think we've found one.

00:20:04.610 --> 00:20:05.650
We're unconvinced.

00:20:05.650 --> 00:20:08.200
We put it back together
and went, oh, now it's

00:20:08.200 --> 00:20:09.568
suddenly different.

00:20:09.568 --> 00:20:11.860
And we'll have a slightly
different resonant frequency.

00:20:11.860 --> 00:20:12.340
But let's give it a go.

00:20:12.340 --> 00:20:12.760
Let's give it a go.

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:14.398
So shall we slam
straight into the--

00:20:14.398 --> 00:20:15.190
Straight into the--

00:20:15.190 --> 00:20:16.240
Oh, my goodness.

00:20:16.240 --> 00:20:16.890
--right.

00:20:16.890 --> 00:20:17.520
You're--

00:20:17.520 --> 00:20:18.670
Yeah, yeah, I'm
going to catch it--

00:20:18.670 --> 00:20:19.030
Can I move out of the way?

00:20:19.030 --> 00:20:20.928
--just in case we get unlucky.

00:20:20.928 --> 00:20:22.470
If you get unlucky,
it goes that way.

00:20:22.470 --> 00:20:22.690
Oh, yeah.

00:20:22.690 --> 00:20:24.280
If I get unlucky, it
goes-- right, here we go.

00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:24.610
Here we go.

00:20:24.610 --> 00:20:25.318
Here we go, yeah.

00:20:28.880 --> 00:20:29.480
It's fine.

00:20:29.480 --> 00:20:30.500
Look at it.

00:20:30.500 --> 00:20:32.621
I would happily live
in that building.

00:20:32.621 --> 00:20:35.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:35.990 --> 00:20:37.950
So we've got it moving
at quite a frequency.

00:20:37.950 --> 00:20:39.240
It's shaking--
don't get me wrong.

00:20:39.240 --> 00:20:40.698
It's shaking it
all over the place.

00:20:40.698 --> 00:20:42.080
But it's not falling over.

00:20:42.080 --> 00:20:43.580
What we're going
to do now is, we're

00:20:43.580 --> 00:20:45.950
going to keep the
amplitude the same,

00:20:45.950 --> 00:20:47.373
because we can't adjust it.

00:20:47.373 --> 00:20:49.040
And we're going to
reduce the frequency,

00:20:49.040 --> 00:20:50.165
so we're shaking it less.

00:20:50.165 --> 00:20:51.790
So do you want to
reduce the frequency?

00:20:51.790 --> 00:20:52.980
Slowly, slow, yeah.

00:20:52.980 --> 00:20:53.540
We'll slowly bring
the frequency down.

00:20:53.540 --> 00:20:54.623
I'm going to move as well.

00:20:54.623 --> 00:20:56.710
So now you can stand back.

00:20:56.710 --> 00:20:57.900
There's now less shaking.

00:20:57.900 --> 00:20:59.580
Sorry.

