00:56:16.035 --> 00:56:18.160
Right, so the very last
thing I'm going to show you

00:56:18.160 --> 00:56:21.010
is a problem, once
again, with engineering.

00:56:21.010 --> 00:56:24.210
So we did structural,
like civil engineering.

00:56:24.210 --> 00:56:26.710
We're now going
to look at, well,

00:56:26.710 --> 00:56:30.030
engineering that
brought down a rocket.

00:56:30.030 --> 00:56:33.300
There was a rocket,
the Ariane 5 rocket,

00:56:33.300 --> 00:56:35.160
which was being launched by ESA.

00:56:35.160 --> 00:56:39.000
And 40 seconds after it
took off, it exploded.

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:40.920
Thankfully, it was
unstaffed, right?

00:56:40.920 --> 00:56:42.630
There were no humans onboard.

00:56:42.630 --> 00:56:45.870
It was just payload
of other spacecraft.

00:56:45.870 --> 00:56:48.393
But of course, someone had
built those spacecraft.

00:56:48.393 --> 00:56:50.310
And they were obviously
very attached to them.

00:56:50.310 --> 00:56:55.740
And a simple mathematical error
caused the rocket to explode.

00:56:55.740 --> 00:57:00.840
And the spacecraft rained
down on the swamp underneath.

00:57:00.840 --> 00:57:03.990
And I will explain what the
maths mistake was in a second.

00:57:03.990 --> 00:57:06.660
But the bits of
spacecraft, they then

00:57:06.660 --> 00:57:09.330
sent them back to the
people who had made them

00:57:09.330 --> 00:57:11.640
and were waiting to
