So these are bits of
instruments that we

00:57:46.630 --> 00:57:48.510
flew on the Cluster spacecraft.

00:57:48.510 --> 00:57:50.742
So there's four of them,
actually, so four of them--

00:57:50.742 --> 00:57:51.700
All on the same rocket?

00:57:51.700 --> 00:57:53.560
All on the same rocket, yeah.

00:57:53.560 --> 00:57:55.300
That was a big mistake.

00:57:55.300 --> 00:57:57.440
And they posted them
back to the lab?

00:57:57.440 --> 00:57:57.940
Yes.

00:57:57.940 --> 00:58:01.230
So when the rocket obviously
came down, as you said,

00:58:01.230 --> 00:58:04.510
not that long after launch,
it fell into the swamp

00:58:04.510 --> 00:58:06.010
in French Guiana.

00:58:06.010 --> 00:58:08.350
And so the European
Space Agency had

00:58:08.350 --> 00:58:10.240
people who could go out
and rescue the rocket

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:11.890
and get the pieces back.

00:58:11.890 --> 00:58:15.190
So we then got our
instruments sent back.

00:58:15.190 --> 00:58:17.410
And apparently, I wasn't
there at the time,

00:58:17.410 --> 00:58:19.090
but the story goes
that we got the box.

00:58:19.090 --> 00:58:20.007
And they opened it up.

00:58:20.007 --> 00:58:21.640
And there was still
bits of swamp in it

00:58:21.640 --> 00:58:23.810
and bits of our instrument, too.

00:58:23.810 --> 00:58:27.320
So this is one of
the brains of one

00:58:27.320 --> 00:58:28.570
of the instruments on Cluster.

00:58:28.570 --> 00:58:31.120
So we built the instrument
that measures-- well, we

00:58:31.120 --> 00:58:32.620
can talk about what
the mission did.

00:58:32.620 --> 00:58:35.920
But it was sent up to
study the environment

00:58:35.920 --> 00:58:38.132
around the Earth, so the
magnetic field of the Earth

00:58:38.132 --> 00:58:39.340
and the particle environment.

00:58:39.340 --> 00:58:41.007
And this is the brains
of the instrument

00:58:41.007 --> 00:58:43.390
that measured the electrons
in the environment

00:58:43.390 --> 00:58:44.350
around the Earth.

00:58:44.350 --> 00:58:45.680
And what research do you do?

00:58:45.680 --> 00:58:46.180
You're on--

00:58:46.180 --> 00:58:48.190
So my research is
really related.

00:58:48.190 --> 00:58:49.600
I study the Sun.

00:58:49.600 --> 00:58:53.170
And I'm interested in how
the Sun's activity impacts

00:58:53.170 --> 00:58:54.670
the Earth's magnetic
field, creating

00:58:54.670 --> 00:58:56.050
something called space weather.

00:58:56.050 --> 00:58:58.420
And this Cluster
mission was designed

00:58:58.420 --> 00:58:59.650
to study space weather.

00:58:59.650 --> 00:59:01.570
So one of the
things that did was

00:59:01.570 --> 00:59:04.150
look at the physical processes
behind the generation

00:59:04.150 --> 00:59:06.250
of the aurora, the
northern lights.

00:59:06.250 --> 00:59:10.270
And the aurora are
generated by solar activity.

00:59:10.270 --> 00:59:11.260
That sounds useful.

00:59:11.260 --> 00:59:13.218
I mean, I say what do
you do like I don't know.

00:59:13.218 --> 00:59:15.992
I'm actually married to
Lucy, just so we're--

00:59:15.992 --> 00:59:17.200
because otherwise, that was--

00:59:17.200 --> 00:59:18.617
I thought it was
quite convincing.

00:59:18.617 --> 00:59:21.340
If your parents are watching,
they're like, he never asked.

00:59:21.340 --> 00:59:24.440
So we've got meteorite rings.

00:59:24.440 --> 00:59:24.940
Look at us.

00:59:24.940 --> 00:59:26.667
Ah, nerds.

00:59:26.667 --> 00:59:27.250
No, it's fine.

00:59:27.250 --> 00:59:27.470
It's fine.

