still covered in rocket fuel.

00:59:37.820 --> 00:59:38.320
So--

00:59:38.320 --> 00:59:39.130
And that's not good for you.

00:59:39.130 --> 00:59:39.700
It's not good for you.

00:59:39.700 --> 00:59:40.840
And I don't want
to get on my hands

00:59:40.840 --> 00:59:42.050
and then go and eat
my dinner later.

00:59:42.050 --> 00:59:44.230
But I mean, it's pretty
cool to see these bits that

00:59:44.230 --> 00:59:45.790
are completely mangled up.

00:59:45.790 --> 00:59:48.640
And normally, our
instruments don't come back.

00:59:48.640 --> 00:59:51.130
So these bits were built
in our laboratories.

00:59:51.130 --> 00:59:53.073
And now we've got
them back again.

00:59:53.073 --> 00:59:54.490
I think, on one
of them, there was

00:59:54.490 --> 00:59:57.640
a little tag that said
UCL's Mullard Space Science

00:59:57.640 --> 00:59:58.290
Laboratory.

00:59:58.290 --> 01:00:00.760
So someone was like, you
know, if found, please send it

01:00:00.760 --> 01:00:01.840
home to us.

01:00:01.840 --> 01:00:04.240
They figured that would
take millions of years

01:00:04.240 --> 01:00:06.190
and be some distant
civilization.

01:00:06.190 --> 01:00:07.890
But no, it was within our--

01:00:07.890 --> 01:00:09.910
Yeah, so you can see.

01:00:09.910 --> 01:00:12.482
And so when you arrived--
you started working there

01:00:12.482 --> 01:00:13.690
just after this had happened.

01:00:13.690 --> 01:00:14.930
Just after this had happened.

01:00:14.930 --> 01:00:18.583
So when we launched the
spacecraft, of course,

01:00:18.583 --> 01:00:19.750
we want to have a big party.

01:00:19.750 --> 01:00:21.250
Everyone gets
together to celebrate.

01:00:21.250 --> 01:00:24.700
And they'd bought champagne
to drink after the launch.

01:00:24.700 --> 01:00:26.740
And I arrived about
two years later.

01:00:26.740 --> 01:00:30.157
And that champagne was still
there, sadly, undrunk, yeah.

01:00:30.157 --> 01:00:32.240
But I mean, we could talk
about the success story,

01:00:32.240 --> 01:00:35.713
because we did go on to
rebuild these instruments.

01:00:35.713 --> 01:00:36.880
So they were launched again.

01:00:36.880 --> 01:00:38.410
They were launched again, yes.

01:00:38.410 --> 01:00:40.840
So the European Space
Agency gave us the money

01:00:40.840 --> 01:00:42.230
to rebuild the instruments.

01:00:42.230 --> 01:00:43.650
And it took much less time.

01:00:43.650 --> 01:00:47.257
So within four years, they had
been rebuilt and relaunched.

01:00:47.257 --> 01:00:48.340
And they're still running.

01:00:48.340 --> 01:00:49.423
And they're still running.

01:00:49.423 --> 01:00:50.950
So we launched in 2000.

01:00:50.950 --> 01:00:51.790
And what are we now?

01:00:51.790 --> 01:00:53.243
2019.

01:00:53.243 --> 01:00:54.910
The ones that are in
space now are still

01:00:54.910 --> 01:00:55.660
operating successfully.

01:00:55.660 --> 01:00:57.035
Wow, because this
blew up in '96.

01:00:57.035 --> 01:00:57.550
'96.

01:00:57.550 --> 01:00:59.140
So they really did turn
around quite quick.

01:00:59.140 --> 01:00:59.360
Yeah.

01:00:59.360 --> 01:00:59.840
That's amazing.

01:00:59.840 --> 01:01:00.340
Yeah.

01:01:00.340 --> 01:01:02.913
And so we actually-- we were
chatting to a friend of yours.

