This was literally last night.

01:01:05.020 --> 01:01:05.800
We were chatting to a friend.

01:01:05.800 --> 01:01:08.020
And she was like, oh, I was
watching the live stream,

01:01:08.020 --> 01:01:11.360
because my PhD was
going to be on Cluster.

01:01:11.360 --> 01:01:13.090
And so she was a
first-year PhD student

01:01:13.090 --> 01:01:14.680
watching the live stream.

01:01:14.680 --> 01:01:16.210
And we were like, what happened?

01:01:16.210 --> 01:01:18.780
And she was like,
the room was silent.

01:01:18.780 --> 01:01:19.780
And then everybody left.

01:01:19.780 --> 01:01:21.660
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:21.660 --> 01:01:22.160
Wow.

01:01:22.160 --> 01:01:26.006
And she was like, well,
different PhD, I guess.

01:01:26.006 --> 01:01:28.080
And so where do these live now?

01:01:28.080 --> 01:01:30.600
So these live in my department.

01:01:30.600 --> 01:01:32.520
We have some on display,
because as I said,

01:01:32.520 --> 01:01:33.990
we built four instruments.

01:01:33.990 --> 01:01:37.590
So we've got quite a lot
of this mangled hardware.

01:01:37.590 --> 01:01:39.300
And we, yeah, we keep them out.

01:01:39.300 --> 01:01:42.540
We talk to people about the
mission, talk about what we did

01:01:42.540 --> 01:01:44.070
successfully to launch again.

01:01:44.070 --> 01:01:46.020
And I think it just
serves as a reminder

01:01:46.020 --> 01:01:48.300
