01:01:59.344 --> 01:02:02.732
[APPLAUSE]

01:02:03.700 --> 01:02:07.100
It's all right.

01:02:07.100 --> 01:02:09.770
People spend so long
working on a spacecraft.

01:02:09.770 --> 01:02:11.780
Like, a mission is
decades to get it to work.

01:02:11.780 --> 01:02:15.290
And they have some of them out
in the coffee room at the lab,

01:02:15.290 --> 01:02:17.270
just like in the glass
case, so a reminder

01:02:17.270 --> 01:02:19.340
for the next generation
of space scientists

01:02:19.340 --> 01:02:22.340
that your decades of
work may disappear

01:02:22.340 --> 01:02:25.820
in a fraction of a second
and land in a swamp.

01:02:25.820 --> 01:02:28.910
And what happened
with that was, there

01:02:28.910 --> 01:02:35.000
was one sensor in the navigation
part of the Ariane 5 rocket

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:38.420
which-- well, so this
part of the rocket

01:02:38.420 --> 01:02:40.700
took input from several sensors.

01:02:40.700 --> 01:02:43.250
It took the raw data coming
in from those sensors,

01:02:43.250 --> 01:02:46.280
converted it into meaningful
navigation information,

01:02:46.280 --> 01:02:48.380
and then sent that to
the main processor that

01:02:48.380 --> 01:02:51.500
was kind of driving the
rocket, if you will.

01:02:51.500 --> 01:02:53.360
And when the numbers
were coming in,

01:02:53.360 --> 01:02:55.790
they had to work out how
big they were going to be,

01:02:55.790 --> 01:02:59.030
because you have to allocate
a certain amount of memory.

01:02:59.030 --> 01:03:03.530
And they tended to allocate
just 16 bits, 16 ones and zeros,

01:03:03.530 --> 01:03:05.030
for a value coming in.

01:03:05.030 --> 01:03:06.540
But some of them
might be bigger.

01:03:06.540 --> 01:03:08.540
They could be up to 64.

01:03:08.540 --> 01:03:11.588
And so what they did, because
they could have just written

01:03:11.588 --> 01:03:13.130
something in the
programme which was,

01:03:13.130 --> 01:03:17.000
for every input that comes in,
check how big it is before you

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:18.680
try and send it into the memory.

01:03:18.680 --> 01:03:20.590
But that's quite
processor intensive.

01:03:20.590 --> 01:03:24.050
And they had quite strict
limitations on how much power

01:03:24.050 --> 01:03:25.280
they were allowed to use.

01:03:25.280 --> 01:03:27.620
And so instead of checking
every single sensor,

01:03:27.620 --> 01:03:29.660
they looked for all
the sensors which

01:03:29.660 --> 01:03:33.770
could give a number bigger
than 16 binary digits.

01:03:33.770 --> 01:03:37.280
And they would check those
to avoid any problems.

01:03:37.280 --> 01:03:39.500
And the ones that never
could be that big,

01:03:39.500 --> 01:03:40.690
they didn't bother checking.

01:03:40.690 --> 01:03:42.190
And they could save
some processing.

01:03:42.190 --> 01:03:46.760
And that all worked really,
really well on the Ariane 4.

01:03:46.760 --> 01:03:49.940
They then copied
it to the Ariane 5

01:03:49.940 --> 01:03:51.740
without double checking.

01:03:51.740 --> 01:03:54.010
And because of a different
take-off trajectory

01:03:54.010 --> 01:03:55.850
and because of the way
the sensors worked,

01:03:55.850 --> 01:03:57.440
one of the sensors
that previously

01:03:57.440 --> 01:04:00.500
wasn't being checked, well,
continued to not be checked,

01:04:00.500 --> 01:04:02.240
but now should
have been checked.

01:04:02.240 --> 01:04:04.220
And it actually
didn't have to be on.

01:04:04.220 --> 01:04:06.590
They just left it
on after launch.

01:04:06.590 --> 01:04:10.640
It was a prelaunch sensor,
because if there was ever a go

01:04:10.640 --> 01:04:13.010
to launch, and then they
aborted before takeoff,

01:04:13.010 --> 01:04:15.258
and then they reset, it
took forever to reset.

01:04:15.258 --> 01:04:17.050
So they didn't turn
them off straight away.

01:04:17.050 --> 01:04:19.700
They let them run for a while
and then turned them off

01:04:19.700 --> 01:04:22.950
once they were sure it
was definitely safe.

01:04:22.950 --> 01:04:25.430
However, it continued
to run as it took off.

01:04:25.430 --> 01:04:26.990
It got a value that was too big.

01:04:26.990 --> 01:04:29.030
It didn't fit in the
memory it put it in.

01:04:29.030 --> 01:04:31.310
It rolled over to the
memory next to it.

01:04:31.310 --> 01:04:35.690
And the whole thing crashed,
which, in and of itself,

01:04:35.690 --> 01:04:39.230
wouldn't have been the worst
thing, because it could have

01:04:39.230 --> 01:04:41.570
restarted or something,
except it was designed

01:04:41.570 --> 01:04:43.400
to give a crash report.

01:04:43.400 --> 01:04:46.040
So like the stereotypical,
someone's like, ah,

01:04:46.040 --> 01:04:48.410
tell my spouse I love
them, but this is like,

01:04:48.410 --> 01:04:52.220
ah, tell my debugger the
following crash context

01:04:52.220 --> 01:04:53.570
information.

01:04:53.570 --> 01:04:57.770
And so it sent the debug
message up the same link

01:04:57.770 --> 01:05:00.650
to the main processor, which
didn't know that could happen.

01:05:00.650 --> 01:05:02.402
It thought it was
navigation data,

01:05:02.402 --> 01:05:04.610
thought the rocket had
suddenly gone off to one side,

01:05:04.610 --> 01:05:07.280
tried to correct, except it
hadn't gone off to one side.

01:05:07.280 --> 01:05:10.310
And the correction threw
it off to one side.

01:05:10.310 --> 01:05:11.300
It tore it apart.

01:05:11.300 --> 01:05:12.980
The self-destruct
sequence kicked in.

01:05:12.980 --> 01:05:16.070
And because a
64-digit number was

01:05:16.070 --> 01:05:19.370
tried to put in
a 16-digit space,

01:05:19.370 --> 01:05:21.920
this whole rocket exploded.

01:05:21.920 --> 01:05:24.830
And possibly-- because the
spacecraft weren't insured,

01:05:24.830 --> 01:05:25.970
which is amazing--

01:05:25.970 --> 01:05:28.450
however, ESA did decide
to refund it, right?

01:05:28.450 --> 01:05:32.970
So one slight maths error can
have phenomenal implications.

01:05:32.970 --> 01:05:36.840
And that is pretty
much it from me.

01:05:36.840 --> 01:05:39.455
I guess, in conclusion, I
started with the theory of,

01:05:39.455 --> 01:05:41.150
are mistakes important?

01:05:41.150 --> 01:05:43.730
And in some cases, yes.

01:05:43.730 --> 01:05:45.333
We have to get the maths right.

01:05:45.333 --> 01:05:47.000
I mean, we'll get it
wrong occasionally.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:48.890
But we have to get
it right in a lot

01:05:48.890 --> 01:05:50.150
of these critical situations.

01:05:50.150 --> 01:05:53.360
And that means we need
people who are good at maths

01:05:53.360 --> 01:05:56.540
and are prepared to put the
effort in, because with maths,

01:05:56.540 --> 01:05:59.270
we can do more than our brains
were originally built to do,

01:05:59.270 --> 01:05:59.770
right?

01:05:59.770 --> 01:06:02.480
We can go beyond our intuition,
which I think is incredible.

01:06:02.480 --> 01:06:05.253
But ironically, to get
mathematicians and people who

01:06:05.253 --> 01:06:07.670
are prepared to put the effort
in, and work hard, and more

01:06:07.670 --> 01:06:09.045
importantly, come
up with systems

01:06:09.045 --> 01:06:11.300
that accept that humans
will make mistakes,

01:06:11.300 --> 01:06:13.400
and we can use our
same mathematical logic

01:06:13.400 --> 01:06:15.440
to have robust
systems where mistakes

01:06:15.440 --> 01:06:17.450
don't become disasters--

01:06:17.450 --> 01:06:19.040
to have all of
that, we need people

01:06:19.040 --> 01:06:21.990
who weren't afraid to make
mistakes to learn mathematics,

01:06:21.990 --> 01:06:22.490
right?

01:06:22.490 --> 01:06:24.830
So I guess the other
goal of my book,

01:06:24.830 --> 01:06:27.230
as well as showing people
all the incredible critical

01:06:27.230 --> 01:06:29.930
mathematics that underpins
our modern society,

01:06:29.930 --> 01:06:32.300
I also wanted to encourage
people to have a go.

01:06:32.300 --> 01:06:36.170
Maths is difficult. But
the people who enjoy maths

01:06:36.170 --> 01:06:37.910
are not the people
who find it easy.

01:06:37.910 --> 01:06:40.250
They're the people who
enjoy how difficult it is.

01:06:40.250 --> 01:06:41.240
It's hard work.

01:06:41.240 --> 01:06:42.260
You get it wrong.

01:06:42.260 --> 01:06:44.555
But gradually, it will teach
your brain how to think.

01:06:44.555 --> 01:06:46.430
And gradually, you will
get better and better

01:06:46.430 --> 01:06:47.780
at mathematics.

